<title>USA: USDA allots $170 mln to states for water quality.</title>
<headline>USDA allots $170 mln to states for water quality.</headline>
<dateline>WASHINGTON 1997-03-10</dateline>
<text>
<p>The U.S. Agriculture Department allocated $170 million to states for use in the new Enviromental Quality Improvement Program, which is aimed at safeguarding water purity.</p>
<p>Farmers will be able to request EQIP funding after final rules for the program take effect, probably in April.</p>
<p>EQIP will be used primarily in state priority areas -- watersheds or regions with special environmental sensitivity or significant soil, water or related natural resource concerns.  </p>
<p>Under EQIP, USDA would provide cost-share aid for up to 75 percent of the cost of conservation practices such as grassed waterways, manure management facilities, capping wells or improving wildlife habitat.</p>
<p>Texas would receive the largest amount, $13.7 million, followed by Kansas, $6.65 million, and Montana, $6.35 million.</p>
<p>Congress created EQIP as part of the 1996 farm policy law. EQIP was authorized for $200 million a year. USDA said the final $30 million for fiscal 1997 would be divided among states later for technical, financial and educational assistance.  </p>
